The paper deals with a computational problem related to genetics and DNA sequencing, which suggests that it could belong to several sub-categories in computer science. The use of binary matrix factorization and alternating minimization techniques indicates that it could be categorized under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The analysis of convergence properties and theoretical bounds suggests that it could also belong to cs.IT (Information Theory). The application of the proposed technique to real-world datasets suggests that it could be categorized under cs.CE (Computational Biology and Bioinformatics) and cs.CG (Computational Geometry).
